<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="102" type="known host and adult behavior">
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="102">Known host and adult behavior.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="102">
Known only from 
<taxonomicName class="Echinoidea" family="Loveniidae" genus="Breynia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Breynia vitis-idaea" order="Spatangoida" pageId="15" pageNumber="102" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="vitis-idaea">Breynia vitis-idaea</taxonomicName>
. The adult is the pollinator of the host plant (
<bibRefCitation author="Kawakita, A" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="23" pageNumber="110" pagination="410 - 415" title="Evolution of obligate pollination mutualism in New Caledonian Phyllanthus (Euphorbiaceae)." url="10.3732/ajb.91.3.410" volume="91" year="2004 b">Kawakita and Kato 2004b</bibRefCitation>
). Eggs are placed in the interspace between the tepal and ovary (Fig. 8H), so the ovipositor does not penetrate floral tissue. Larva feeds on seeds.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="102" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="102">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="102">
In Japan occurs widely in the Ryukyu Archipelago (Fig. 9E). Known also from China (
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang, J" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="24" pageNumber="111" pagination="43 - 54" title="Six new species of the genus Epicephala Meyrick, 1880 (Lepidoptera: Gracillariidae) associated with Euphorbiaceae plants." volume="3275" year="2012 a">Zhang et al. 2012a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
